properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms tonight over Northwestern Ontario. The main threat is ping-pong ball sized hail. Heavy rain and strong wind gusts are also threats. ### Very large hail can damage property, break windows, dent vehicles and cause serious injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm. For more information: http://www.emergencymanagementontario.ca/english/beprepared/beprepared.html.
Expires: 2020-06-08T10:19:04-00:00

properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert: Overland Flow Flood Alert Updated
properties.Summary:
Description: Due to overland flooding, all provincial highways in Lac La Biche County are closed to non-essential traffic by order of Alberta Transportation. This includes Highways 36, 55 in both directions, 881, 858, 855, 663, 866 and 867. This closure is in effect until further notice. Due to high rainfall, there is still a possibility of sewer backups and basements flooding. ### Visit www.laclabichecounty.com for further updates.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The first heat event of the season will begin today and last through Tuesday. Temperatures will reach 30 degrees Celsius today, before falling to 18 degrees Celsius tonight. Temperatures on Tuesday will reach 29 degrees Celsius again before a cooler air mass moves in to the region. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
